post_text: In our YCSD Restart Smart Plan for the 2020-2021 School Year, the school district stated that we would re-evaluate the plan at Labor Day to determine if any adjustments were needed. Given the number of students in attendance in grades 6-12, the district has decided to return all grades to a four day a week hybrid schedule. Our students who are attending school on the hybrid model will still have assignments to complete on Mondays virtually and the students who are on the total virtual learning plan will continue to be on that plan. Please be assured that this change will keep numbers in classes low enough to maintain the social distancing expectations. This change does not affect the elementary schools. We will begin this on Tuesday September 15, 2020. If you have any questions or concerns, please contact the school at which your child attends or email us at questions@yazoo.k12.ms.us.

COVID-19 Restrictions Update Due to the state mandate allowing only 25% capacity at athletic events, Yazoo County High School will pre-sell 450 tickets for Friday’s game versus Yazoo City. Players, cheer, and band will have first opportunity to purchase tickets (2 per participant) before allowing students and public to purchase. Students and public tickets will be on a “first come” basis until sold out. Visitor tickets will be delivered to opposing school for distribution, and visitor admission fee will be collected at gate with the presentation of the “visitor ticket”. All tickets are $7 an no tickets will be sold at the gate.

There will be no free/discounted admission unless you present an MHSAA state pass

Yazoo County School District students who have been struggling with their Chromebook not connecting to HughesNet internet service provider, please complete the following steps:

We recommend you contact Hughesnet Support
(1-866-347-3292) for instructions on making the following setting changes.

1. Disable IPV6 address conversion

2. Disable any Web Acceleration or Turbo

Once these changes are made through your internet service provider, the student chromebook will connect and have the same content filtering as when it is on campus.

Feel free to contact Helpdesk help@yazoo.k12.ms.us with any concerns or problems.

post_text:
Public Budget Hearing at 6:00 p.m

A public hearing as required by law will be conducted by the Yazoo County School Board on June 30, 2020. The purpose of the hearing is to give the citizens of the Yazoo County School District an opportunity to comment on the expenditures and taxing plans of the district. Items to be discussed are the District’s Budget, Special Education Funding, Preschool Funding as well as Federal Program Funding for Fiscal Year 2021.

The meeting will be held at the Boardroom of the Office the Superintendent of Education of Yazoo County School District. The hearing will begin at 6:00 p.m.

Due to the COVID-19 pandemic mitigating recommendations, the administrative building will only be open to essential employees of the Yazoo County School District. The public hearing will be broadcast live on Facebook at the above date and time.

A call in number is available to ask questions: (425) 436-6357. A pin number can be obtained by emailing a request to pin@yazoo.k12.ms.us.
Questions will be taken from the chat session of the Facebook live stream.

Class of 2020 graduates:
Due to a production issue related to the COVID pandemic, Jostens was not able to provide the embossed diploma covers in time for our graduation ceremony. However, Mr. Tally and his crew at Jostens delivered the personalized diploma covers earlier this week and we would love for you to come by the school and pick it up. Also, several of the Senior Yard Signs still remain in the cafeteria. These were purchased by the school and are available to you free of charge.

Please make plans to come to the school and collect your items next week between 8am and 3pm Monday- Thursday.

Sincerely-
Amy Trammell
Graduation Coach

post_text: Bentonia Gibbs Elementary and Yazoo County Schools would like to welcome new teacher assistant Bailey Hudson. Ms. Hudson graduated from Tri-County Academy in 2017. She is currently a student through Delta State University working towards a Bachelors degree. In her spare time, she loves to go shopping, being in the outdoors, and hanging out with friends and family. Ms. Bailey said, “I have felt the calling to be a teacher from a young age and I’m so blessed with the opportunity to work at Bentonia Gibbs while pursuing my degree towards this career.”

We would like to welcome 5th grade science teacher, Martishia Powers. Mrs. Powers is a graduate of Yazoo County High School. She earned her Bachelors of Science degree in Biology from Mississippi State University. Mrs. Powers is married to Willie Powers Jr. and they have two children, Willie III (7) and Maliah (3). They reside in Madison, MS.
Mrs. Powers is on the Board of Directors for “Our Kids Matter of MS, INC.” She has worked closely with non profit organizations throughout the state to help support youth and their surrounding communities. She enjoys spending time and making memories with her family. She is so excited to come back to the community in which she lived to help give back to the children of Bentonia Gibbs.

We are proud to welcome Mrs. Brooklyn Sparnecht to Bentonia Gibbs Elementary School. She will serve as a Speech-Language Pathologist. Mrs. Sparnecht graduated in May of 2019 with a Master’s in Communicative Disorders from Jackson State University. Prior to that, she received a Bachelor’s in Speech-Language Pathology from Mississippi University for Women.
She is originally from Louisville, MS but now lives in Madison with her husband, Dylan, and dog, Boss. They are also expecting a new member of their little family who will make his or her arrival in December.
Her passion is working with children of all ages and backgrounds, helping to make communication accessible and successful for all.
Welcome, Mrs. Sparnecht, to the Yazoo County Family.

He likes watching college football, participating in weekly church services, and is an avid astronomer.

post_text:
Welcome to Yazoo County!!! Assistant Band Director!!!

Chadijah Craig was born and raised in Charlotte, North Carolina. She graduated from Jackson State with a bachelors in Music Performance and received a Masters in Music performance from Pennsylvania State University. She is a passionate music educator dedicated to the academic and personal success of all students. Her teaching philosophy is based around the awareness that all students are designed and created for a purpose. She has a motto that says “Once you identify what your purpose is on Earth, therein lies the keys to the door of EVERYTHING you could ever want or need". As a first-generation college grad, she has made it her duty to help shift the paradigms of all students she encounters.

post_text:
Congratulations!!!

Sarah Elizabeth is the daughter of Mrs. Melanie Hardy. Sarah will graduate with high honors from Holmes Community College on Friday, May 15. At the recent virtual Award’s Day Program, she has received the Social and Behavioral Science Department Award, the Phi Theta Kappa Golden Key Award, and was one of only five people from the college to be named to the Phi Theta Kappa All-Academic Team. At the recent virtual Cheer Award’s Banquet, she received the Sophomore Award as well as the Fitness Award. At HCC, Sarah Elizabeth serves as a cheerleader, an Ambassador, and is the President of the Kappa Alpha Chapter of Phi Theta Kappa. She also serves as a leader in the Social and Behavioral Honors Class and was nominated for the Hall of Fame. While at HCC, Sarah Elizabeth has been named to the President’s List, as a Scholar Athlete, and received the Freshman Award in Cheer. In the fall, Sarah Elizabeth plans to attend Delta State University to pursue a degree in Psychology.

post_text:
Yazoo County School District Family:

As you know, the first round of instructional packets are due on Monday, April 6th. As a school district, we are going to continue to move forward with this date. You may bring the instructional packets back in the manila envelope(s) that you received them in on March 25th to your student’s respective school.

Please place your child’s name on the envelope as well as the grade level. If possible in reference to the high school, place the subject on the envelope.

While turning in the first packet, you should pick up the second instructional packet which will be turned in on Monday, April 20th. If students are in school, they can bring the packet with them; if not, the packet will be dropped off at school much like this upcoming Monday.

In regards to the middle and high school, MDOT has the entry road closed; however, according to the officers at the barricade, they will let you through to go and turn in work.

There will be more information forthcoming in reference to pre-k and kindergarten registration on Monday.

Bentonia Gibbs Elementary School
March 26 at 3:34 PM ·

Thank you so much for everyone’s patience as we prepared “Instructional Packets” for our students! Over 150 packets were distributed! We re-grouped after a busy day yesterday, and today was smooth sailing! We have plenty of packets left for every grade. You may continue to pick them up from 9-11 a.m. with meals on Friday, Monday, and Tuesday. Before 9 and after 11:00 you will be able to pick packets up from the file cabinets in front of the school. Please be sure all students have their packets before Wednesday. Thank you again for your support during this unusual time!

Yazoo County High School
March 25 at 2:24 PM ·

What an AWESOME “packet pick up” day we had! Over 170 YCHS students now have instructional packets in their hands!

Remember-if you need help, your teachers are on standby! Email them and ask questions!!

For those of you struggling with math, Khan Academy is a wonderful online resource!
(This has been the most sought after resource)

If you were unable to pick up today-we will be doing it again tomorrow from 8-12. Please do not get out of your vehicle! Call the school and let us know who you are picking up for and it will be brought out to you!

It’s a GREAT day to be a Panther!

post_text:
Yazoo County Panther students
I want to let you know that we have missed seeing you at school this past week. I hope you are all doing well, being safe and taking care of yourselves. The faculty, staff and administration care about you guys.

We will have a few things for you to work on while you are out....but along with that I want you to do three more things....have some fun, be physically active playing each day, and read something you're interested in learning about. Try your best to read at least two books each week.

We will be out of school until April 20th at least. We are going to be checking with you and your parents as much as we can. Be safe. You guys are our next generation leaders, so keep reading, keep thinking and keep growing.

post_text: Based on the Governor's announcement today, all schools are closed until Friday April 17th (as of this point, return will be no earlier than Monday April 20th). We are continuing to work on our plans for providing online/distance learning options for our students as well as a plan to provide breakfasts and lunches to the students in our county and will have further information on this by Friday March 20, 2020. Please continue to monitor our district website (www.yazoo.k12.ms.us), social media pages and may use our AIM notification system for announcements going forward. Please be safe and thank you for your patience during this time.

The Mississippi Department of Education (MDE) is aware that school communities are concerned about the outbreak of the respiratory illness caused by COVID-19 (also known as the coronavirus) that is occurring in several countries, including the United States.



There are currently no cases of COVID-19 in Mississippi. However, the MDE is in contact with the Mississippi Department of Health (MSDH), the state epidemiologist, the Mississippi Emergency Management Agency (MEMA), and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) regarding preventive measures and preparation in the event of a local outbreak.



This email provides guidance and resources to support the health and well-being of students, school and district employees, and communities. This information is posted at www.mdek12.org/COVID19 and will be updated as new information becomes available.

post_text:
Yazoo Valley’s 2020 Youth Tour students had the privilege of meeting some of the state’s top leaders. The students had breakfast with Rep. Kenneth Walker. Senator Joseph Thomas gave the students the opportunity to stand on the senate floor. The Governor, Lieutenant Governor and the Secretary of State delivered motivating speeches to the group. The day concluded with team building exercises and fellowship.
#msylp20

Great Experience for our very own Lucas Clark.
